default&#xa0;
defaultThe principles of 
defaulta locally led
default approach have been 
defaultchampioned
default 
defaultin
default a range of significant contributions
default from 
defaultthe Heseltine Review, the Social Mobility Commission led by Alan Mi
defaultlburn, and also the Work Foundation, London School of Economies, the Institute of Public Policy Research
default among others.
default&#xa0;defaultLocal authority tracking of young peopledefault&#xa0;defaultLocal authorities have a responsibility to track young people as part of their statutory duties to encourage and support participation, and improve outcomes for young people.  
default&#xa0;
defaultOfsted’s Annual Report references the percentage of young people unknown to lo
defaultcal authorities, which is on average 4 per cent of 16 and 17 year olds. It 
defaultstates that
default ‘in some 
defaultl
defaultocal authorities the percentage is as high as 23 per cent’. This is misleading. Only 7 councils have more than 10 per cent of young people unknown, only 2 coun
defaultcils 
defaulthave 
defaultabove 15 per cent and only 1 council 
defaulthas 
defaultabove 20 per cent. Furthermore, in the last year, the percentage of young people unknown 
defaultto local authorities 
defaulthas fallen in 
defaulteach of 
defaultthese 7 councils
default by as much as 13 per cent.  This 
defaultimprovement 
defaultis 
defaultnot refe
defaultrenced by the report. 
default&#xa0;
defaultNevertheless
default,
default we are keen to support councils wanting to improve further, and the
default LGA
default recently launched a Tracking Guide and Planning Toolbox, which builds on the innovative practice in some ‘expert’ local authorities for 
defaultthose 
defaultwant
defaulting to improve how they track young people
default. In undertaking this 
defaultwork,
default it 
defaultbeca
defaultme clear that local authority success is dependent on the contribution 
defaultof
